{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Keep current text, add TN explaining 形/形而上 structure",
    "content": "1. Yes, it's a significant loss — but not a fatal one. The passage's argument (Dao is highest/metaphysical, Li is lowest/phenomenal) survives in English. What's lost is the structural elegance: the reader can't see that the word for \"metaphysical\" literally contains and surpasses the word for \"phenomenal.\" That's not just wordplay — it's the argument performing itself at the lexical level. The containment relation (形 inside 形而上) mirrors the philosophical claim (the phenomenal is subsumed within the metaphysical).\n\n2. Yes, a TN is warranted here. This is exactly the kind of case where a translator's note earns its keep — it reveals structural content that English cannot carry.\n\n3. I would NOT use \"above-the-phenomenal\" in the running text. Hyphenated neologisms are clumsy, they break reading flow, and they call attention to the translator rather than the text. The current rendering (\"the metaphysical\" / \"the phenomenal\") is clean and does its job.\n\nMy recommendation: keep the current translation as is, and add a TN along these lines:\n\n\"TN: The Chinese 形而上 (xingershang, 'metaphysical') literally means 'above form (形, xing),' where 形 alone denotes the phenomenal or formal. The author's sentence exploits this structure: 道 is 形而上 (above form) while 礼 is 形 (form itself). The containment of 形 within 形而上 mirrors the philosophical claim that the phenomenal is subsumed within the metaphysical. This structural relation is unavailable in the English 'metaphysical'/'phenomenal' pair.\"\n\nThis lets the reader reconstruct the argument's full force without burdening the running text."
  }
}
